					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-2497516#post-3578325</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-2497516/scp-3105#post-3578325</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Fri, 25 Aug 2017 14:38:16 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>reiskahax</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3303853</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Pretty OK. It's written pretty clinically. The logs are also a great touch. But it seems that this wouldn't be <strong>that</strong> anomalous. I mean, yes. A virus that basically destroys your memories is weird, but this doesn't seem <strong>that</strong> weird.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-2497516#post-3563559</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-2497516/scp-3105#post-3563559</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 02 Aug 2017 16:45:12 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>MrWrong</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2039383</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Not getting behind this. While the description is definitely befitting of the clinical tone, I don't see how it would be anomalous. Sure, this is unusual, but MotheR Nature has many unusual things created. I find it somewhat contrived, as I don't see how this virus stands out from other normal viruses that have unusual infection traits.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
